{"id":"2104.09613","submitter":"Everton  Medeiros","authors":"Everton S Medeiros, Ulrike Feudel, Anna Zakharova","title":"Asymmetry-induced order in multilayer networks","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. E 104, 024302 (2021)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevE.104.024302","report-no":null,"categories":"nlin.AO nlin.CD","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Symmetries naturally occur in real-world networks and can significantly\ninfluence the observed dynamics. For instance, many synchronization patterns\nresult from the underlying network symmetries, and high symmetries are known to\nincrease the stability of synchronization. Yet, here we find that general\nmacroscopic features of network solutions such as regularity can be induced by\nbreaking their symmetry of interactions. We demonstrate this effect in an\necological multilayer network where the topological asymmetries occur\nnaturally. These asymmetries rescue the system from chaotic oscillations by\nestablishing stable periodic orbits and equilibria. We call this phenomenon\nasymmetry-induced order and uncover its mechanism by analyzing both\nanalytically and numerically the suppression of dynamics on the system's\nsynchronization manifold. Moreover, the bifurcation scenario describing the\nroute from chaos to order is also disclosed. We demonstrate that this result\nalso holds for generic node dynamics by analyzing coupled paradigmatic\nR\\\"ossler and Lorenz systems.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 6 Apr 2021 13:11:30 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 2 Sep 2021 08:42:19 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-09-03"}
{"id":"2104.11607","submitter":"Luca Fabbri","authors":"Flora Moulin, Luca Fabbri, Aur\\'elien Barrau","title":"Cross section for Bhabha and Compton scattering beyond quantum field\n  theory","comments":"7 pages","journal-ref":"Int.J.Theor.Phys.60:1692(2021)","doi":"10.1007/s10773-021-04791-3","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.gen-ph hep-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We consider the theory of spinor fields written in polar form, that is the\nform in which the spinor components are given in terms of a module times a\ncomplex unitary phase respecting Lorentz covariance. In this formalism, spinors\ncan be treated in their most general mathematical form, without the need to\nrestrict them to plane waves. As a consequence, calculations of scattering\namplitudes can be performed by employing the most general fermion propagator,\nand not only the free propagator usually employed in QFT. In this article, we\nuse these quantities to perform calculations in two notable processes, the\nelectron-positron and Compton scatterings. We show that although the\nmethodology differs from the one used in QFT, the final results in the two\nexamples turn out to give no correction as predicted by QFT.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 6 Apr 2021 12:40:15 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-06-01"}
